This paper discusses the modernization of traditional connection establishment, flow control, sequence number splitting, acknowledgement, and flow scheduling mechanisms for use with multiple paths in communication networks. It also analyzes the stability and convergence of multipath rate control and discusses various multipath congestion control algorithms. These topics are all related to network protocols and algorithms, which are typically covered in the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of multipathing in datacenters, which falls under the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also discusses congestion control, which is a topic covered in the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. The paper also discusses the history and evolution of the transport layer, which is a topic covered in the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the remaining challenges and research issues, which is a topic covered in the Architecture (cs.AR) sub-category.
